  "local_port": 42370,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What do I eat on the Ketogenics Diet?",
  "response": "The ketogenic or \"keto\" diet is a low-carbohydrate, high-fat diet that shares many similarities with the Atkins and low-carb diets. The goal of the keto diet is to put your body into a metabolic state called ketosis, where it efficiently burns fat for energy instead of carbohydrates.\n\nHere's a list of foods you can eat on the ketogenic diet:\n\n1. **Meats and Poultry**: Beef, chicken, turkey, pork, lamb, and other meats are allowed. Stick to unprocessed, natural meats.\n\n2. **Fatty Fish**: Salmon, trout, mackerel, and other fatty fish are excellent sources of healthy fats and protein.\n\n3. **Eggs**: Eggs are a staple on the keto diet, and you can prepare them in various ways.\n\n4. **High-Fat Dairy**: Cheese, butter, heavy cream, and other high-fat dairy products are allowed, but be mindful of carb content in some dairy products.\n\n5. **Nuts and Seeds**: Almonds, walnuts, flaxseeds, pumpkin seeds, chia seeds, and others are great for snacking, but monitor portion sizes as they can be high in carbs.\n\n6. **Healthy Fats and Oils**: Olive oil, coconut oil, avocado oil, and butter are the primary sources of fat on the keto diet.\n\n7. **Avocados**: Avocados are high in healthy fats and can be used in various dishes.\n\n8. **Low-Carb Vegetables**: Leafy greens like spinach, kale, and lettuce, along with other non-starchy vegetables like broccoli, cauliflower, zucchini, and cucumbers, are great choices.\n\n9. **Berries**: In moderation, berries such as strawberries, blueberries, and raspberries can be consumed.\n\n10. **Condiments**: You can use salt, pepper, herbs, and spices to add flavor. Be cautious with sauces and dressings, as they can contain hidden carbs.\n\nHere are some foods to avoid on the ketogenic diet:\n\n1. **Grains and Starches**: Wheat, rice, pasta, cereal, and other grains are high in carbs and should be avoided.\n\n2. **Sugary Foods**: Candy, soda, ice cream, and other sweets are high in sugar and carbs.\n\n3. **Most Fruits**: Fruits are high in sugar and should be limited. Stick to berries in moderation.\n\n4. **Legumes**: Beans, lentils, chickpeas, and other legumes are high in carbs.\n\n5. **Root Vegetables**: Potatoes, carrots, parsnips, and other root vegetables are high in carbs.\n\n6. **Low-Fat and Diet Products**: These often contain added sugar and other carbs.\n\n7. **Alcohol**: Alcoholic beverages can be high in carbs and can interfere with ketosis.\n\n8. **Unhealthy Fats**: Trans fats and highly processed oils should be avoided.\n\nHere's a sample one-day meal plan on the keto diet:\n\n- **Breakfast**: Scrambled eggs with spinach and cheese, cooked in coconut oil, with a side of avocado.\n- **Lunch**: Grilled salmon with a side of asparagus and a mixed green salad with olive oil dressing.\n- **Dinner**: Beef stir-fry with broccoli, bell peppers, and zucchini, cooked in sesame oil.\n- **Snacks**: A handful of almonds or macadamia nuts, or celery sticks with almond butter.\n\nRemember to monitor your carbohydrate intake and keep it below 50 grams per day to maintain ketosis. Staying hydrated and supplementing with electrolytes can also help manage the transition into ketosis. Always consult with a healthcare professional before starting any new diet.",
